<L N="161">Vppone myne hede A crowne &thorn;ey sett</L>
<L>thornes thorowe myn brayne &thorn;ei mette</L>
<L>The pennes &thorn;at &thorn;e letteres wretyne</L>
<L>Werene scourges &thorn;at I was wyt smetene<MILESTONE N="45b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="165">how many lettyrs there-one bene</L>
<L>Rede and &thorn;oue maye wete &amp; seene</L>
<L>V<SUP>e</SUP> Milia V. C.l And x<SUP>e</SUP></L>
<L>Wondes one myn body both rede &amp; wane</L>
<L>for to schewe &thorn;e of loue-dede</L>
<L N="170">My-selfe I wol the charture rede</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD><I>O vos omnes qui transitis per viam</I></HEAD>
<L>&yogh;e mene &thorn;at gone forth in &thorn;e weye</L>
<L>takyth hede and lokyth with your eye</L>
<L>And redyth vppone this parchement</L>
<L>&yogh;if any sorowe be so gret as myne</L>
<L N="175">&yogh;et stondyth and heryth &thorn;e charture rede</L>
<L>why I Am wondyd &amp; all for-blede</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD><I>Sciant presentes &amp; futuri</I></HEAD>
<L>wote &yogh;e &thorn;at be here and be fore to come</L>
<L>&THORN;at Ihesu of na&yogh;areth goddes sone</L>
<L>vndrestond &yogh;e wyl &thorn;at wollyn Abyde</L>
<L N="180">&THORN;at Ihesu hath now A blody syde</L>
<L>&THORN;at bore was in bedleme</L>
<L>of marye offered in Ierusaleme</L>
<L>&THORN;e kynges sone of heuene a-boue</L>
<L N="184">A mercyfull fadyr &thorn;at wel I loue
