<L>Derworth sowle &thorn;ou art me lef</L>
<L>Myn Erytage &thorn;at ys so fre</L>
<L>In &thorn;y myschef to &yogh;eue hit &thorn;e</L>
<L>And when &thorn;at sesyng y &yogh;eue shulde</L>
<L N="40">A dede as &thorn;e jewys wolde
<PB REF="00000175.tif" N="51"></L>
<L N="41">Vntyll a mayde y be-toke me</L>
<L N="42">When &thorn;at y conceyued shulde be</L>
<L N="a">ffull wordyly she kepte me</L>
<L N="b">Tyll &thorn;e tyme fulfylled shuld be</L>
<L N="43">The mayde was trwe mylde &amp; fre</L>
<L>She me reseyued for loue of &thorn;e</L>
<L N="45">Nyne monethes with her y was</L>
<L>To make amendes for &thorn;y trespas</L>
<L>Or y ynto &thorn;is worlde was borne</L>
<L>To saue mankynde &thorn;at was forlorn</L>
<L>Thorow &thorn;e vertu of my grace</L>
<L N="50">Thus kome &thorn;is sesyng fyrst in place</L>
<L>Vyrgyn Mary mayden mylde</L>
<L>With me went grette with chylde</L>
<L>And when &thorn;is sesyng was all y-do</L>
<L>Grete enuye hadde &thorn;y fo</L>
<L N="55">That cursedde fend satanas</L>
<L>Hadde gret won&thorn;er why hit was</L>
<L>Wherfor j wolde so myche loue &thorn;e</L>
<L>That so vnkynde hast be to me</L>
<L>Wroth he was hit helpede hym no&yogh;t</L>
<L N="60">For to helpe &thorn;e was all my &thorn;ow&yogh;t</L>
<L>He tempted me yn so gret foly</L>
<L>An pride couetyse &amp; glotenye</L>
<L>And well he wyste y was a man</L>
<L>But synne yn me fonde he none</L>
<L N="65">ffor-so&thorn;e well harde he &thorn;retened me</L>
<L>How &thorn;at sesyng shuld dere y-bow&yogh;t b[e]</L>
<L>For to destroye me &thorn;orow his m[y&yogh;ht]</L>
<L N="68">And putte &thorn;e for euer out of m[y sy&yogh;ht]
<PB REF="00000177.tif" N="53"></L>
<L N="69">Now dereworth soule herken [to me]</L>
<L N="70">And a newe joye shall y telle [&thorn;e]</L>
<L>To make a chartur of feffem [ent]</L>
<L>Heuen &amp; er&thorn;e shall be pres[ent]</L>
<L>Hit moste nedus in suche man[er be]</L>
<L>That y most &yogh;olde my lyf fo[r &thorn;e]</L>
<L N="75">And when y am deed man &thorn;e[n be &thorn;ou kynde]</L>
<L>And haue &thorn;is chartyr euer yn &thorn;[y mynde]</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;yn enmy &thorn;at hath &thorn;e so[w&yogh;ht]</L>
<L>And &yogh;yt shall y lose &thorn;e now&yogh;[t]</L>
<L>ffor y woll dye for &thorn;y foly</L>
<L N="80">And brynge &thorn;e yn-to my cu[mpanye]</L>
<L>I am lyf and &thorn;ou art dede</L>
<L>Call &thorn;ou my lyf a&yogh;eyn &thorn;y [nede]</L>
<L>ffor to helpe &thorn;e y am redy</L>
<L>To saue &thorn;e euer fro &thorn;yn en[my]</L>
<L N="85">ffor many a way haue y [goo]</L>
<L>In hunger &thorn;ryste chele &amp; woo</L>
<L>Thrytty wyntyr &amp; &thorn;re &thorn;erto</L>
<L>Or my desese wer all y-do</L>
<L>Parchemyn to fynde wyste y none</L>
<L N="90">To make a chartur a&yogh;ens &thorn;y fone</L>
<L>That wolde laste with-owten ende</L>
<L N="92">Herken now to my wordes hende
<PB REF="00000179.tif" N="55"></L>
<L N="93">But as trewe loue ladde<NOTE PLACE="foot">The <I>de</I> in this word has a stroke over it.</NOTE> me &thorn;o</L>
<L>Myn owene skyne y take &thorn;er-to</L>
<L N="95">And when y hadde so y-do</L>
<L>Well fewe frendes hadde y tho</L>
<L>To gete me frendes y &yogh;af gret mede</L>
<L>As &thorn;oth &thorn;e pore &thorn;at hath myche nede</L>
<L>But to gyf &thorn;e y hadde no more</L>
<L N="100">ffor &thorn;y sowle &thorn;at was forlore</L>
<L>Then my sowle y &yogh;af for &thorn;e</L>
<L>ffor to dye vpon a tre</L>
<L>Vpon a thursday a sowper y made</L>
<L>To frend &amp; fo to make hem glade</L>
<L N="105">Of breed &amp; wyne &thorn;e sacrament</L>
<L>ffor euer to be my testament</L>
<L>Whych ys my flesh &amp; my blode</L>
<L>To &thorn;o &thorn;at lyuen yn mykyll mode</L>
<L>And to &thorn;em &thorn;at dyen out of charite</L>
<L N="110">Her dampnacyon for euer to be</L>
<L>Her wyll y &yogh;ou fowr wordes teche</L>
<L>[A]nd to &thorn;e pepull loke &yogh;e hem preche</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD><I>Hoc facite in meam commemoracionem</I></HEAD>
<L>[&THORN;]o &thorn;at haue hem euer yn mynde</L>
<L>[H]ygh mede in heuen shull &yogh;e fynde</L>
<L N="115">These wordes towchen &thorn;e sacrament</L>
<L N="116">That men resseyuen verament
<PB REF="00000181.tif" N="57"></L>
<L N="117">Hyt semyth mony &amp; ys but on</L>
<L>Hyt semyth brede &amp; hit ys none</L>
<L>Hyt ys qwylke &amp; semeth deed</L>
<L N="120">Hyt ys my body in forme of breed</L>
<L>Thys made y only for mankynde</L>
<L>[M]y won&thorn;erfull werkes to haue yn mynde</L>
<L>Who so reseyue hit yn clennesse</L>
<L>[S]aued shall be &amp; come to blysse</L>
<L N="125">[A]nd to haue yn mynde my passyon</L>
<L>That shall be &thorn;y saluacyon</L>
<L>Ere y fro &thorn;e bord arose</L>
<L>Of my dyscypull betrayd y wose</L>
<L>When he had sowped he rose a-non</L>
<L N="130">To grete maystres ryde he gone</L>
<L>And brow&yogh;t hem with hym yn &thorn;e way</L>
<L>As a lyon goth abowte his pray</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD><I>Suscepit me sicut leo paratus ad predam</I></HEAD>
<L>Anon &thorn;ey begon to spoyle me</L>
<L>And sayde y shulde dye vpon a tre</L>
<L N="135">My mantell &amp; o&thorn;er clo&thorn;us mo</L>
<L>All y hadde hem sone for-go</L>
<L>They caste lotte as wolde befall</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;er on shuld hem or parte hem all</L>
<L>So all my clo&thorn;us fro me &thorn;ey token</L>
<L N="140">And all my frendus me for-soken
<PB REF="00000183.tif" N="59"></L>
<L N="141">Naked y stod among my fone</L>
<L>ffor o&thorn;er sokour hadde y none</L>
<L>Redy &thorn;ey wer me for to dysese</L>
<L>But none &thorn;e was me to plese</L>
<L N="145">They made skourges hwge &amp; grete</L>
<L>Therwith my body for to bete</L>
<L>And &thorn;ow&yogh; y wolde haue playned me</L>
<L>Ther shulde to me no sokour haue be</L>
<L>ffull sore aferd for-so&thorn;e y was</L>
<L N="150">When &thorn;ey ledde me so gret a pase</L>
<L>To a pyler y was bownd all ny&yogh;t</L>
<L N="152">Tugged &amp; beten tyll hit was day ly&yogh;t</L>
<L N="153">And wasshen with my owene blode</L>
<L>That on &thorn;e yr&thorn;e abowte me flode</L>
<L N="155">And so y suffred all &thorn;e ny&yogh;t</L>
<L>Tyll on morn hit was day-ly&yogh;t</L>
<L>Streyned well harde to a tre</L>
<L>As parchemyn oweth for to be</L>
<L>Herkeneth now &amp; &yogh;e shall wyten</L>
<L N="160">How &thorn;e chartur was wryten
<PB REF="00000185.tif" N="61"></L>
<L N="161">Ouer all my face fyll &thorn;e ynke</L>
<L>With &thorn;ornus &thorn;at in my hedde gonne synke</L>
<L>The pennus &thorn;at &thorn;ose letterus wryten</L>
<L>Wer skourges &thorn;at y was with smyten</L>
<L N="165">How many letterus &thorn;at &thorn;er-on bene</L>
<L>Rede &amp; &thorn;ou may wyte &amp; sene</L>
<L>ffyue &thorn;owsande fyue hundered &thorn;en</L>
<L>Won&thorn;us of my body rede &amp; wanne</L>
<L>ffor to shew &thorn;e of my loue-dede</L>
<L N="170">My-self wyll here &thorn;e chartur rede</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD><I>O vos omnes qui transitis per viam attendite uidete si est dolor sitis sicut dolor meus</I></HEAD>
<L N="171">&yogh;e men &thorn;at gon her by &thorn;e way</L>
<L>Beholde &amp; se both ny&yogh;t &amp; day</L>
<L>And redeth vpon &thorn;is parchmyn</L>
<L>&yogh;yf any sorow be so gret as myn</L>
<L N="175">Ston&thorn;eth &amp; herkeneth &thorn;is chartur redde</L>
<L>Why y am wounded &amp; all forbledde</L>
<L>Wyten &thorn;o &thorn;at ben her &amp; &thorn;o &thorn;at ben to come</L>
<L>That y ihesu of na&yogh;areth goddus sone</L>
<L>Vn&thorn;erstondeth well &yogh;e &thorn;at woll abyde</L>
<L N="180">That y ihesu haue a blody syde</L>
<L>That borne was yn bedleem</L>
<L>Ouer-more offred yn-to iherusalem</L>
<L>The kyngus sone of heuen aboue</L>
<L N="184">A mercyfull fader &thorn;at y so well loue
<PB REF="00000187.tif" N="63"></L>
<L N="185">I made a sesyng when y was borne</L>
<L>To saue mankynde &thorn;at was forlorne</L>
<L>But with my cha[r]tur her-yn present</L>
<L>I make to mannus sowle a feffement</L>
<L>That y haue granted &amp; &yogh;eue</L>
<L N="190">To mankynde with me to lyue</L>
<L>In my kyngdon of heuen blysse</L>
<L>To haue &amp; to holde withowten mysse</L>
<L>With &thorn;is condycyon so &thorn;at &thorn;ou be kynde</L>
<L>And haue &thorn;is chartor euer yn mynde</L>
<L N="195">ffrely to haue &amp; frely to holde</L>
<L>With alle &thorn;e pertynanse to be bolde</L>
<L>In my blesfull joye euer to dwelle</L>
<L>For &thorn;e rente &thorn;at y shall &thorn;e telle</L>
<L>Myn herytage &thorn;at ys so fre</L>
<L N="200">ffor omage or ellys for fewte</L>
<L>No more woll y aske of &thorn;e</L>
<L>But a fowr leued grasse &yogh;elde to me<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Nota</I> in margin.</NOTE></L>
<L>That on lef ys verry shryfte with hert</L>
<L>That<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. <I>Tath.</I></NOTE> o&thorn;er ys for synne sorowe smerte</L>
<L N="205">The &thorn;ryrde ys y wyll no more do so</L>
<L>The fowr&thorn;e ys do &thorn;y penanse &thorn;er-to</L>
<L>And when &thorn;ese leuus togeder be sette</L>
<L N="208">A trewe loue men klepe hyt
<PB REF="00000189.tif" N="65"></L>
<L N="209">Of &thorn;is rente be not behynde</L>
<L N="210">The way to heuen &thorn;en may &thorn;ou fynde</L>
<L>And &yogh;yf &thorn;ou trewely &thorn;is rente pay me</L>
<L>My grete mercy &thorn;en shall y shewe &thorn;e</L>
<L>ffor &yogh;yf &thorn;ou falle &amp; grettely mystake</L>
<L>&yogh;yt my charter wyll not &thorn;at y &thorn;e forsake</L>
<L N="215">&yogh;yf &thorn;ou amende &amp; mercy craue</L>
<L>Thyn erytage so&thorn;ly &thorn;en shalt &thorn;ou haue</L>
<L>The sele &thorn;at hit ys a-seled wyth</L>
<L>Hyt was made at no smy&yogh;th</L>
<L>Of golde ne syluer ys hit now&yogh;th</L>
<L N="220">Ne stele ny yren ys hit of wro&yogh;th</L>
<L>But with a spere my hert was stongen</L>
<L>Thorow my syde &amp; thorow my longen</L>
<L>Vpon my syde &thorn;at made a wonde</L>
<L>&THORN;at my hert blode ran down to &thorn;e grownde</L>
<L N="225">And with yren naylus &thorn;ey boredden me</L>
<L>Thorw fote &amp; honde yn-to &thorn;e tre</L>
<L>The sesynge wax was dere y-bow&yogh;t</L>
<L>Alle myn herte rote hit was y-sow&yogh;t</L>
<L>All y-compered with fyn vermelon</L>
<L N="230">Of my rede blode &thorn;at ran adown</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD><I>Factum est cor meum tanquam liques|sens in medio uentris mei</I></HEAD>
<L>ffyue seles be sette &thorn;ervpon</L>
<L N="232">ffadyr &amp; sone god &amp; mon
<PB REF="00000191.tif" N="67"></L>
<L N="233">The fyfte ys &thorn;at &thorn;ou beleue most</L>
<L>That y kam of &thorn;e holy goste</L>
<L N="235">And &thorn;erfor her may &thorn;ou now se</L>
<L>That y am a kyng of gret powste</L>
<L>In playn power &thorn;y state to make</L>
<L>A crowne of &thorn;ornus on my hedde y take</L>
<L>Thys crowne betokene&thorn; &thorn;at y am kyng</L>
<L N="240">And frely may &yogh;ef myn owene &thorn;yng</L>
<L>Thys wytnessed &thorn;e jewys alle</L>
<L>On kneus &thorn;ey gan before me falle</L>
<L>And lowde sayde yn her skornyng</L>
<L>All hayle lorde &amp; of jewes &thorn;e kyng</L>
<L N="245">Betwene two &thorn;euus &thorn;is charter was seled</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e wer seke &thorn;at on was heled</L>
<L>Betwene two theuus hy&yogh;e y-pyght</L>
<L>In token &thorn;at y was lord of my&yogh;th</L>
<L>This be tokeneth both good &amp; yll</L>
<L N="250">At &thorn;e day of dome how y may saue or spyll</L>
<L>Well drye y was &amp; thursted sore</L>
<L>But of such drynk my&yogh;th y no more</L>
<L>ffor aysell &amp; galle &thorn;ey &yogh;ef to me</L>
<L>But on drynke aske y of &thorn;e</L>
<L N="255">That &thorn;ou be louyng towards &thorn;y fone</L>
<L N="256">O&thorn;er drynke of &thorn;e aske y non
<PB REF="00000193.tif" N="69"></L>
<L N="257">&yogh;ef &thorn;ou me loue haue &thorn;is yn mynde</L>
<L>To &thorn;y enemyes be &thorn;ou ryght kynde</L>
<L>Ensaumpull &thorn;ou my&yogh;t take her of me</L>
<L N="260">For loue of my fone y honge on tre</L>
<L>But my fadyr y pray the</L>
<L>Vpon my enemyes &thorn;at &thorn;ou haue pyte</L>
<L>And as y do. do &thorn;ou to &thorn;yne</L>
<L>Then saued shalt &thorn;ou be fro helle pyne</L>
<L N="265">He ben wytnesses mo &thorn;en on</L>
<L>Marke mathew luke &amp; jon</L>
<L>And namely my modyr swete</L>
<L>That for me blody teres gan lete</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;er she stode vn&thorn;er &thorn;e rode</L>
<L N="270">She sawe my body all on blode</L>
<L>That fro my foot vnto my hedde</L>
<L>I was not ellys but blode reed</L>
<L>No worde to me my&yogh;th she speke</L>
<L>Hit semed well her hert wolde breke</L>
<L N="275">No won&thorn;er hit was &thorn;ow&yogh; she wer woo</L>
<L>When she sawe me on &thorn;e crosse so y-do</L>
<L>ffor sorow of her y made a cry</L>
<L N="278">And sayde well lowde <I>hely lama&yogh;abatany</I>
<PB REF="00000195.tif" N="71"></L>
<L N="279">Anon she fell down yn swonyng</L>
<L N="280">Ther be-for me at my dyyng</L>
<L>The paynus &thorn;at y suffred wer full sore</L>
<L>But for my moder &thorn;e wer well more</L>
<L>When y layde my hedde her &amp; &thorn;er</L>
<L>My mo&thorn;er changed all he[r] chere</L>
<L N="285">ffull fayn she wolde haue holpen me</L>
<L>But for &thorn;e jewys hit my&yogh;t not be</L>
<L>The paynus &thorn;at y hadde wer full smert</L>
<L>The swerde of sorow persedde her hert</L>
<L>When seyn john y her betoke</L>
<L N="290">She caste on me a drwly loke</L>
<L>As &thorn;ow&yogh; y hadde her all forsake</L>
<L>And to an-o&thorn;er sone her be-take</L>
<L>And or &thorn;is charter wryten &thorn;us was</L>
<L>ffull ofte she sayde Alas Alas</L>
<L N="295">Vpon my shuldur y layde myn hedde</L>
<L>When y &thorn;row&yogh; faste vnto my deed</L>
<L>ffor so bare y was of worldly gode</L>
<L>When y shulde dye vpon &thorn;e rode</L>
<L>That y ne hadde wher-of to take</L>
<L N="300">Reste to myne hedde wher-of to make</L>
<L>Pouer &amp; ryche haue &thorn;is yn mynde</L>
<L N="302">When &thorn;ou yn &thorn;is worlde no reste kan fynde
<PB REF="00000197.tif" N="73"></L>
<L N="303">What reste y hadde only for &thorn;e</L>
<L>When y henge nayled vpon a tre</L>
<L N="305">Well may &thorn;ou knowe &thorn;at y hadde none</L>
<L>ffor ther y was among my fone</L>
<L>And when &thorn;ou among &thorn;y fone art brow&yogh;t</L>
<L>Be redy to suffre with all &thorn;y &thorn;ow&yogh;t</L>
<L>To stonde at &thorn;e barre hit ys well harde</L>
<L N="310">As &yogh;e bene wor&thorn;y to take rewarde</L>
<L>Thou &thorn;at for me sufferest wronge</L>
<L>&THORN;ou shalt stonde on my ri&yogh;t honde</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou &thorn;at vengest &thorn;e on &thorn;y brodyr</L>
<L>Ther stondest &thorn;ou not but on &thorn;at odyr</L>
<L N="315">&yogh;yf &thorn;u wyll &thorn;e so&thorn;e knowe</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;th as &thorn;ou sowest so sha[l]t &thorn;u mowe</L>
<L>I fele me now so full of wo</L>
<L>That out of &thorn;is worlde y moste go</L>
<L>With peynus of &thorn;eth harde am y bownde</L>
<L N="320">My sowle shall passe her yn a stounde</L>
<L>Beholde now mon with herte &amp; ye</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;y loue how y shall dye</L>
<L>I honge on crosse for loue of &thorn;e</L>
<L>ffor-sake &thorn;e synne for loue of me</L>
<L N="325">Mercy &thorn;ou aske &amp; amende &thorn;e sone</L>
<L N="326">And y woll for&yogh;yf &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast mysdone
<PB REF="00000199.tif" N="75"></L>
<L N="327">ffor full of mercy y am trewly</L>
<L>To all &thorn;o &thorn;at woll cryn for mercy</L>
<L>What shall hit greue to repente &thorn;e</L>
<L N="330">And yn endeles joye to dwelle with me</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;o &thorn;at woll no mercy crye</L>
<L>They go to helle when &thorn;ey shall dye</L>
<L>Now when y haue oo worde spoken</L>
<L>My yen togeder y most lokene</L>
<L N="335">Now synfull man haue pyte on me</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;y owene sowle for charyte</L>
<L>Thys worde y most ne&thorn;us speke</L>
<L>And &thorn;en myn herte shall to-breke</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD><I>Consummatum est</I></HEAD>
<L>&thorn;is chartur ys done</L>
<L N="340">Man now hast &thorn;ou ouercome &thorn;y fone</L>
<L>Anon to helle y went &thorn;is charter to shewe</L>
<L>Before sathanas &thorn;at mykyll shrewe</L>
<L>Thus y hym shent &amp; brow&yogh;t to grounde</L>
<L>Thorow my paynes of spytuus wounde</L>
<L N="345">And after a couenante made &thorn;er was</L>
<L>Betwene me &amp; sathanas</L>
<L>All my catell to haue a-way</L>
<L>That he berafte me with his play</L>
<L>The &thorn;rydde day y rose &amp; made a feste</L>
<L N="350">To &thorn;e moste &amp; to &thorn;e leste
<PB REF="00000201.tif" N="77"></L>
<L N="351">The feste was of joye &amp; blys</L>
<L>Estur day called hit ys</L>
<L>Oon endentur y lafte with &thorn;e</L>
<L>Wher-of &thorn;ou shalt euer sykur be</L>
<L N="355">In &thorn;e preestus honde my flessh &amp; blode</L>
<L>That for &thorn;e was honged on &thorn;e rode</L>
<L>Ho-so-euer hit be &thorn;at beleueth &thorn;er-on</L>
<L>Endeles payne shall he fynde none</L>
<L>All-&thorn;ow&yogh;e y dye &yogh;et dyeth not he</L>
<L N="360">For vp shall he ryse &amp; leue with me</L>
<L>A well fayr syngne y toke &thorn;e her also</L>
<L>A token of &thorn;e crosse &thorn;at y was on do</L>
<L>To bere with &thorn;e wher-euer &thorn;ou go</L>
<L>To saue &thorn;e euer fro &thorn;y fo</L>
<L N="365">To my fader now moste y go</L>
<L>ffor all hys wyll now haue y do</L>
<L>Her y take my leue &yogh;o haue me seyne</L>
<L>At &thorn;e day of dome y come agayne</L>
<L>Mon to dome aftyr hys werke</L>
<L N="370">Thys ys to beleue of all holy kyrke</L>
<L>And euer after yn joye to dwelle</L>
<L>Saued to be fro &thorn;e paynes of helle</L>
<L>But a kote Armour y ber her with me</L>
<L N="374">The whych y toke of &thorn;y lyuere
<PB REF="00000203.tif" N="79"></L>
<L N="375">The kote ys both ryche &amp; fyne</L>
<L>The campe ys now of rede satyne</L>
<L>A well fayr mayde hit tow&yogh;te</L>
<L>And out of her bowr y hit brow&yogh;te</L>
<L>Powdered hit ys now with fyfe roses rede</L>
<L N="380">With won&thorn;us &thorn;at y &thorn;oled with paynes of dede</L>
<L>And when y come a&yogh;eyn to &thorn;e</L>
<L>Be my clo&thorn;yng &thorn;ou mayst knowe me</L>
<L>And &thorn;o &thorn;at ben of &thorn;er rente behynde</L>
<L>And &thorn;es wondus woll not haue y mynde</L>
<L N="385">ffull sore shall &thorn;ey be a-ferde</L>
<L>When &thorn;is chartur shall be redde</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e hy&yogh; justys be &thorn;ey full ware</L>
<L>For &thorn;ere shall he non spare</L>
<L>ffor all &thorn;at euer &thorn;ou hast wro&yogh;th</L>
<L N="390">ffro &thorn;y yowth &thorn;en shall be sow&yogh;th</L>
<L>But power of my fader y haue</L>
<L>To saue all &thorn;o &thorn;at mercy wyll craue</L>
<L>And pay &thorn;y rente &yogh;yf &thorn;u haue space</L>
<L>&yogh;yf &thorn;ou of me wolte haue grace</L>
<L N="395">And yf &thorn;ou dye full so&thorn;enly</L>
<L>Vpon &thorn;y sowle y shall haue mercy</L>
<L>A couenaunt ys made betwen vs to</L>
<L N="398">As y haue do so most &thorn;ou do
<PB REF="00000205.tif" N="81"></L>
<L>Loke what &thorn;y pater noster sayth to &thorn;e</L>
<L N="400">Lyke as y for&yogh;eue for&yogh;yf &thorn;ou me</L>
<L>Do &thorn;eraftur &yogh;yf &thorn;at &thorn;ou wylte</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;y sowle be not spylte</L>
<L>Vpon all holy wryte y may put me</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;er y be curteys or not to &thorn;e</L>
<L N="405">Be &thorn;ou lered or be &thorn;ou lewed</L>
<L>The weye to heuen y haue &thorn;e shewed</L>
<L>Be &thorn;e tyxte of holy wryte</L>
<L>In what place &thorn;ou wolte seke hyt</L>
<L>Therfor y bydde &thorn;e pay &thorn;e rente</L>
<L N="410">That with &thorn;e fende &thorn;ou be not shente</L>
<L>Wyth me to blysse &thorn;en &thorn;ou shalt come</L>
<L>And yn my blysse &thorn;ou shalt wone</L>
<L>To &thorn;at blysse y may &thorn;e brynge</L>
<L N="414">That of now&yogh;te made &thorn;e &amp; all &thorn;yng</L>
<L>Ihesu yn &thorn;at holy place</L>
<L>Graunte<NOTE PLACE="foot">In the MS. the sign for <I>ra</I> occurs above the <I>n</I>.</NOTE> vs to se &thorn;y holy face Amen</L>
<TRAILER>Explicit
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="ms"><PB REF="00000171.tif" N="47">
<HEAD>CAMB. UNIV. Ff. 2. 38.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>here folowe&thorn; &thorn;e chartur of crifte</HEAD>
<L>Who-so will ouer-rede this boke<MILESTONE N="39b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And wyth hys goostly eye &thorn;er-on loke</L>
<L>To odur scole dar he not wende</L>
<L>To saue hys soule fro the fende<MILESTONE N="40a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="5">Than for to do as &thorn;ys boke tellyth</L>
<L>ffor holy wryte for-sothe hyt spellyth</L>
<L>Wherefore y pray yow for charyte</L>
<L>He that thys boke wyll rede or see</L>
<L>Wyth yowre herte &amp; all yowre mynde</L>
<L N="10">Kepyth derwor&thorn;ely &thorn;at ye here-in fynde</L>
<L>And fulfyllyth hyt in dede</L>
<L>That ye schull now in &thorn;ys boke rede</L>
<L>ffor now stonde ye full styll here anon ry&yogh;t</L>
<L>Yowre sauyour wyll speke to yow ys ty&yogh;t</L>
<L N="15">Wordes of a chartur &thorn;at he hath wroght</L>
<L N="16">That ye now knowe in all yowre tho&yogh;t
<PB REF="00000173.tif" N="49"></L>
<L N="17">And who thys boke can undurstonde</L>
<L>Teche hyt forthe thorow ows &thorn;ys londe</L>
<L>Oon-tyll o&thorn;ur &thorn;at &thorn;ys boke haue now swane</L>
<L N="20">To saue ther soulys ry&yogh;t as &thorn;er owne</L>
<L N="a">ffor he that can and wyll not teche</L>
<L N="b">Hyt ys to drede of full grete wreche</L>
<L N="21">ffor ellys ye can not withowt grete stryfe</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ys worlde passy&thorn; in-to &thorn;e londe of lyfe</L>
<L>Now y wyll begynne to rede ther-one</L>
<L>Hys pees he yeue us euery-chone</L>
<L N="25">Ihesu lorde of heuene and helle</L>
<L>Man &amp; woman y wole yow telle</L>
<L>Loke what prowe y do<NOTE PLACE="foot">Before <I>do</I> the scribe wrote <I>haue</I> and afterwards cancelled it.</NOTE> to &thorn;e</L>
<L N="28">And loke what loue &thorn;ou haste done to me</L>
<L N="29">ffro paradys &thorn;ou were owte pylte</L>
<L N="30">With care &amp; sorowe &thorn;ou were owt y|spylte</L>
<L>And forthe &thorn;ou were dreven a-way</L>
<L>As a beste &thorn;at goyth on-straye</L>
<L>ffor my ryght y come a-downe</L>
<L>To seke the fro towne to towne</L>
<L N="35">To helpe the in thy myschefe</L>
<L>Derworthe soule thou were lefe</L>
<L>Myn herytage that ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">There is a tail on the <I>s</I> in this word.</NOTE> so free</L>
<L>In thy myschefe to yeue thee</L>
<L>And whene &thorn;e sesyng y gyf &thorn;e schulde</L>
<L N="40">I dudd<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Hic et passim</I> after words ending in <I>dd</I> this scribe adds a tail which probably represents a final <I>e.</I></NOTE> as the yewes wolde
<PB REF="00000175.tif" N="51"></L>
<L N="41">Tyll a maydyn y be-toke mee</L>
<L N="42">When y conceyuyd schulde bee</L>
<L N="43">The maydyn was trewe mylde &amp; free</L>
<L>Sche resseyuyd me for loue of thee</L>
<L N="45">Nyne monthes with hur y was</L>
<L>To make amendys for thy trespas</L>
<L>Or y in-to thys<NOTE PLACE="foot">The <I>s</I> in this word is followed by a tail.</NOTE> worlde was borne</L>
<L>To saue mankynde &thorn;at was forlorne</L>
<L>Throrowe my vertue and my grace</L>
<L N="50">Thus came &thorn;ys sesyng fyrste on place</L>
<L>Vyrgyne mary maydyn mylde</L>
<L>Wyth me went &thorn;us grete with chylde</L>
<L>And when &thorn;ys sesynge was all y-do</L>
<L>Well grete envy hadd thy foo</L>
<L N="55">That cursydd fende satanas</L>
<L>Had grete wondur why hyt was</L>
<L>wherefore y wolde so moche loue &thorn;e</L>
<L>That so vnkynde haste &thorn;ou be to me</L>
<L>Wroth he was hyt helpyd hym no&yogh;t</L>
<L N="60">ffor to helpe the was all my &thorn;oght</L>
<L>He tempted me in so grete folye</L>
<L>Pryde couetyse and glotenye</L>
<L>And well he wyste y was a man</L>
<L>But synne in me fonde he none</L>
<L N="65">ffor-sothe ryght harde he threted me</L>
<L>That sesynge schulde haue beten me</L>
<L>ffor to dystroye me &thorn;orow hys my&yogh;t</L>
<L N="68">And put the for-euer owt fro my sy&yogh;t
<PB REF="00000177.tif" N="53"></L>
<L N="69">Now derworthe soule herken to me</L>
<L N="70">And a newe yoye y schall telle to &thorn;e</L>
<L>To make a chartur of feffement</L>
<L>Heuen and erthe schall be presente</L>
<L>But in soche a maner hyt muste be</L>
<L>That y schall &yogh;elde my lyfe for the</L>
<L N="75">And whan y am dede man be &thorn;ou kynde</L>
<L>And haue &thorn;ys chartur euyr in &thorn;y mynde</L>
<L>ffor an enemy that hathe the soght</L>
<L>But y schall for no&thorn;yng lese &thorn;e no&yogh;t</L>
<L>ffor y wold dye for thy folye</L>
<L N="80">And brynge in-to my companye</L>
<L>I am a-lyue and thou art dedd<NOTE PLACE="foot">Or <I>dede?</I></NOTE></L>
<L>I wold yeue my lyfe ayenste &thorn;y quede<MILESTONE N="40b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffor to helpe &thorn;e y am all redy</L>
<L>ffor to saue &thorn;e euer fro &thorn;yn enemye</L>
<L N="85">ffor many a way y haue y-goo</L>
<L>In hungur thurste cheyle &amp; woo</L>
<L>Thretty wyntur &amp; thre therto</L>
<L>Or my dysese were all y-doo</L>
<L>Perchement to fynde wyste y noone</L>
<L N="90">To make thy chartur a-yenste &thorn;y foone</L>
<L>That wolde laste with-owten ende</L>
<L N="92">Herkenyth now to my wordys hende
<PB REF="00000179.tif" N="55"></L>
<L N="93">But as trewe loue badd me doo</L>
<L>Myn owne skynne y toke ther-too</L>
<L N="95">And whan y had so y-doo</L>
<L>Well fewe frendys had y tho</L>
<L>To gete me frendys y gafe grete mede</L>
<L>As do&thorn; &thorn;e pore man &thorn;at ha&thorn; grete nede</L>
<L>But for to yeue &thorn;e had y no more</L>
<L N="100">ffor thy soule that was for-lore</L>
<L>Then my-selfe to yeue for the</L>
<L>That for the dyed vpon a tree</L>
<L>Vpon a thursday a soper y made</L>
<L>To frende &amp; foo to make &thorn;em gladd</L>
<L N="105">Of bredd and wyne the sacrament</L>
<L>ffor euyr to be my testament</L>
<L>whych ys my flesche &amp; my blode</L>
<L>To them &thorn;at leuen in mylde mode</L>
<L>And tho &thorn;at dyen owt of charyte</L>
<L N="110">Ther dampnacioun for euyr to bee</L>
<L>Here wold y my wordes yow teche</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e pepull y pray yow &thorn;em preche</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD><I>Hoc facite in meam commemoracionem</I></HEAD>
<L>And that they haue &thorn;em in mynde</L>
<L>Ther mede in heuene &thorn;ere schull &thorn;ey fynde</L>
<L N="115">These wordes techeth the sacrament</L>
<L N="116"><NOTE PLACE="foot">In the MS. line 116 follows line 117.</NOTE>That men resceyuene verament
<PB REF="00000181.tif" N="57"></L>
<L N="117">Hyt seme&thorn; many hyt ys but oone</L>
<L>Hyt seeme&thorn; bredd and hyt ys noone</L>
<L>Hyt ys quykk and semyth dedd</L>
<L N="120">Hyt ys my body in forme of bredd</L>
<L>Thys made y oonly for mankynde</L>
<L>My wondurfull dedys to haue in mynde</L>
<L>Who-so resceyueth hyt in klennesse<NOTE PLACE="foot">The <I>k</I> is blurred.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sauydd schall be and come to blysse</L>
<L N="125">And to haue in mynde my passyoun</L>
<L>The whych schall be thy sauacioun</L>
<L>Or y fro the borde aroos</L>
<L>Of my dyscypull be-trayed y was</L>
<L>When he had sowpyd he roos anone</L>
<L N="130">To the grete maystyrs he can gone</L>
<L>And bro&yogh;t &thorn;em with hym in &thorn;e way</L>
<L>As a lyone &thorn;at gothe a-bowte hys pray</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD><I>Susceperunt me sicut leo patris ad predam</I></HEAD>
<L>Anon &thorn;ey be-ganne<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>be ganne</I> corrected from <I>be game</I>.</NOTE> to spoyle me</L>
<L>And seydd y schulde dye vpon a tre</L>
<L N="135">My mantell &amp; o&thorn;ur clo&thorn;ys moo</L>
<L>All y hadd &thorn;em sone forgoo</L>
<L>They caste lotte as wolde be-falle</L>
<L>whe&thorn;er oon schulde haue all or parte &thorn;em all</L>
<L>But all my clo&thorn;ys fro me &thorn;ey tokene</L>
<L N="140">And all my frendys me forsokene
<PB REF="00000183.tif" N="59"></L>
<L N="141">Nakyd y stode amonge my foone</L>
<L>ffor odur socour had y noone</L>
<L>Redy &thorn;ey were me for to dysese</L>
<L>But none &thorn;er was me for to plese</L>
<L N="145">They made scorges harde &amp; grete</L>
<L>Ther-with my body schulde be bete</L>
<L>And thoght y wolde haue pleyned me</L>
<L>Ther schulde no socour to me haue bee</L>
<L>ffull sore aferde for-sothe y was</L>
<L N="150">When &thorn;ey ladd me for&thorn;e so grete a pase</L>
<L>To a peler y was bownden all &thorn;e nyght</L>
<L N="152">Scorged &amp; betyd tyl hyt was day-lyght</L>
<L N="153">And waschen with myn owne blood</L>
<L>That on er&thorn;e abowte flode stode</L>
<L N="155">And so y stode bounden all &thorn;e nyght</L>
<L>Tyll on &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">Or &thorn;is?</NOTE> morne &thorn;at hyt was lyght</L>
<L>Streyned well harde vpone a tree<MILESTONE N="41a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>As perchement owyth for to be</L>
<L>Heryth and ye schall weten</L>
<L N="160">How thys chartur was y-wretone
<PB REF="00000185.tif" N="61"></L>
<L N="161">Ouer all the face felle the ynke</L>
<L>Thornys in myn hedd begynne to synke</L>
<L>The pennys &thorn;at &thorn;o letturs<NOTE PLACE="foot">There is a tail after the <I>s</I> in this word.</NOTE> wretyne</L>
<L>Were scorges &thorn;at y was with smetyne</L>
<L N="165">How many letturs that &thorn;er-on bee</L>
<L>Rede &amp; &thorn;ou may wytt and see</L>
<L>ffyve thousande .v.c fyfty &amp; .x. than</L>
<L>woundes on my body rede &amp; wane</L>
<L>ffor to schewe &thorn;e for my loue-dede</L>
<L N="170">My-selfe wolde here the chartyr rede</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD><I>O vos omnes qui transitis per viam attendite &amp; videte si est dolor sitis sicut dolor meus</I></HEAD>
<L N="171">&THORN;e men &thorn;at gone here be &thorn;e way</L>
<L>Be-holde&thorn; &amp; see bo&thorn;e nyght &amp; day</L>
<L>And redy&thorn; vpon thys parchemyne</L>
<L>If eny sorowe be os grete as myne</L>
<L N="175">Stondyth &amp; herkeny&thorn; &thorn;ys chartur redd</L>
<L>Why y am woundedd &amp; all for-bledd</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD><I>Sciant presentes et futuri</I></HEAD>
<L>WETEN &thorn;o &thorn;at ben here &amp; &thorn;o &thorn;at be to come</L>
<L>That y ihesu of na&yogh;are&thorn; godd|is sone</L>
<L>vndurstondy&thorn; well ye &thorn;at wyll abyde</L>
<L N="180">That y ihesu hath a blody syde</L>
<L N="181">Ouer more of-redd in-to Ierusalem</L>
<L N="182">That borne was in bedleme</L>
<L>The kyngys sone of heuen aboue</L>
<L N="184">A mercyfull fadur &thorn;at well y loue
<PB REF="00000187.tif" N="63"></L>
<L N="185">I made a sesynge whan y was borne</L>
<L>To saue mankynde &thorn;at was forlorne</L>
<L>But with my chartur here-in presente</L>
<L>I make to mannys soule a feffement</L>
<L>That y make haue graunted &amp; &yogh;eue</L>
<L N="190">To mankynde with me for to leue</L>
<L>In my kyngdome of heuene blysse<MILESTONE N="41a:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To haue and to holde with-owt mysse</L>
<L>So in thys condycioun &thorn;at &thorn;ou be kynde</L>
<L>And my wonderfull workis to haue in mynde</L>
<L N="195">ffrely to haue and frely to holde</L>
<L>Wyth all &thorn;e purtenaunce for to be bolde</L>
<L>And in my blysfull yoye euer to dwell</L>
<L>ffor the rente &thorn;at y schall &thorn;e telle</L>
<L>Myn herytage that ys so free</L>
<L N="200">ffor homage or ellys for fealte</L>
<L>Nomore wyll y aske of the</L>
<L>But a foure leued grasse &yogh;elde &thorn;ou me</L>
<L>That oon lefe ys very schryfte of hert</L>
<L>That o&thorn;er ys for &thorn;y synne here smert</L>
<L N="205">The thrydd y wyll no more do soo</L>
<L>The four&thorn;e do &thorn;y penaunce mekely &thorn;erto</L>
<L>And &thorn;en &thorn;ese leues to geder byn sett</L>
<L N="208">A trewe loue men callyth hyt
<PB REF="00000189.tif" N="65"></L>
<L N="209">Of thys rente be not be-hynde</L>
<L N="210">The wey to heuene &thorn;ene mytt &thorn;ou fynde</L>
<L>And yf &thorn;ou &thorn;ys rente trewly pay me</L>
<L>My grete mercy wole y schewe &thorn;e</L>
<L>ffor yf &thorn;ou falle &amp; gretly mystake</L>
<L>If my chartour wole &thorn;at y &thorn;e not forsake</L>
<L N="215">If &thorn;ou amende and mercy craue</L>
<L>Thyn herytage so&thorn;ely &thorn;en schalt &thorn;ou haue</L>
<L>The selys &thorn;at hyt ys selyd with</L>
<L>They were made at a smyth</L>
<L>Of golde ne syluyr be &thorn;ey noght</L>
<L N="220">Of stele and yren they were wroght</L>
<L>ffor with a spere of stele my hert was stongen</L>
<L>Thorow my syde &amp; thorow my longene</L>
<L>Vpon my syde &thorn;ey made a wounde</L>
<L>That my herte blode ran to grounde</L>
<L N="225">And with yren nayles they bored me</L>
<L>Thorow fete &amp; hondes in-to &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> tre</L>
<L>The sesynge was dere y-boght</L>
<L>At my herte rote hyt was y-soght<MILESTONE N="41b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>All tempurd with fyne vermyloun</L>
<L N="230">Of my redd blood &thorn;at rane a-downe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD><I>ffactum est cor meum tanquam cera liquescens in medio ventris mei</I></HEAD>
<L>ffyue celys put ther-one</L>
<L N="232">ffadur and sone god &amp; man
<PB REF="00000191.tif" N="67"></L>
<L N="233">The fyrste &thorn;at be-leue muste</L>
<L>That y come of the holy goste</L>
<L N="235">And therfore here may &thorn;ou now see</L>
<L>That y am kyng of prete<NOTE PLACE="foot">Thus the MS. Doubtless an error for <I>state</I>.</NOTE> pouste</L>
<L>In playne power &thorn;ey sate<NOTE PLACE="foot">Thus the MS. <I>Grete?</I></NOTE> to make</L>
<L>A crowne of &thorn;ornys on my hedd y take</L>
<L>Thys be-tokenyth &thorn;at y was kyng</L>
<L N="240">And frely may yeue &thorn;yn owne thyng</L>
<L>Thys wytnessyth &thorn;e yewes all</L>
<L>On knees &thorn;ey can be-fore me falle</L>
<L>And lowde seyde in ther scornyng</L>
<L>All heyle be &thorn;ou of yewes kynge</L>
<L N="245">Betwene ij theues &thorn;e chartur was selyd</L>
<L>Bothe were syke that oon was helydd</L>
<L>Betwne ij theues on hye y-pyght</L>
<L>In tokyn &thorn;at y was kyng of myght</L>
<L>Thys be-tokenyth bothe goode &amp; ylle</L>
<L N="250">At &thorn;e day of dome to saue or spylle</L>
<L>Well drye y was y<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>y</I> is inserted above the line.</NOTE> thursted sore</L>
<L>But of soche drynke my&yogh;t y no more</L>
<L>ffor eysell and galle they yaf to me</L>
<L>But oon drynke y aske of thee</L>
<L N="255">That &thorn;ou be louyng toward &thorn;y foone</L>
<L N="256">Other drynke of the aske y noone
<PB REF="00000193.tif" N="69"></L>
<L N="257">If &thorn;ou me loue haue &thorn;ys in mynde</L>
<L>To thyn enemyes be &thorn;ou kynde</L>
<L>Ensaumpull &thorn;ou my&yogh;t take here of me</L>
<L N="260">ffor loue of my foon y honge on a tre</L>
<L>But mercy fadur y prey the</L>
<L>Vpon myn enemyes haue &thorn;ou petee</L>
<L>And as y do do thou to thyne</L>
<L N="264">Sauyd schalt &thorn;ou be fro helle pyne</L>
<L N="265">Here byn wytnesse mo than oone<MILESTONE N="41b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Marke mathewe luke and Iohne</L>
<L>And namely my moder swete</L>
<L>That for my body teres can lete</L>
<L>ffor there sche stode vndur &thorn;e rode</L>
<L N="270">Sche sawe my body all on bloodd</L>
<L>That fro my fote vnto my hedd</L>
<L>I was noght ellys but all blode redd</L>
<L>Hyt semeth well hur herte wold breke</L>
<L>No worde to me &thorn;ere my&yogh;t sche speke<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. <I>na</I> deleted before <I>my</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="275">No wondur hyt was &thorn;owe sche were wo</L>
<L>When sche sawe me on crosse y-doo</L>
<L>ffor sorowe of hur y made a crye</L>
<L N="278">And seyde well lowde <I>hely lama&yogh;batani</I>
<PB REF="00000195.tif" N="71"></L>
<L N="279">Anon sche felle downe in swownyng</L>
<L N="280">There be-fore me at my dying</L>
<L>The peynes &thorn;at y suffurde were full sore</L>
<L>But for my modur &thorn;ey were &thorn;e more</L>
<L>When y leyde myn hedd here &amp; &thorn;ere</L>
<L>my modur chaunged all hur chere</L>
<L N="285">ffull fayne sche wolde haue holpen me</L>
<L>But for &thorn;e yewes hyt myght not be</L>
<L>Peynes &thorn;at sche suffurde were full smert</L>
<L>The swerde of sorowe perysched hur hert</L>
<L>When to seynt Iohn y hur be-toke</L>
<L N="290">Sche caste on me a drery loke</L>
<L>As thowe y had hur all for-sake</L>
<L>And anothur sone y had be-take</L>
<L>But or &thorn;ys chartur &thorn;us wreten was</L>
<L>Well ofte sche seyde allas allas</L>
<L N="295">Vpon my schouldur y leyde my hedd</L>
<L>Whan y drowe faste vn-to my dedd</L>
<L>ffor so bare y was of worldly goode</L>
<L>When y schulde dye vpon the rode</L>
<L>That y ne hadd where-of to take</L>
<L N="300">Reste to myn hedd for to make</L>
<L>Pore and ryche for to haue in mynde</L>
<L N="302">Whan &thorn;ou in &thorn;e worlde no reste may fynde
<PB REF="00000197.tif" N="73"></L>
<L N="303">What reste y had oonly for the</L>
<L>When y hynge naylyd vpon a tree<MILESTONE N="42a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="305">Well may &thorn;ou know &thorn;at y had none</L>
<L>ffor there y was amonge my foone</L>
<L>And when &thorn;ou among &thorn;y foon art broght</L>
<L>Be redy to suffur wyth all yowre &thorn;oght</L>
<L>To stonde at the barre hyt ys full harde</L>
<L N="310">As ye be worthy to take rewarde</L>
<L>Thou &thorn;at for me suffurste wronge</L>
<L>Thou schalt be so&thorn;ely on my ry&yogh;t honde</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou that vengest the vpone &thorn;y brodur</L>
<L>There stondest &thorn;ou not but on &thorn;at othur</L>
