<DIV2 N="4" TYPE="item">
<HEAD>4. CARTA CELESTIS HEREDITATIS (A Prose Tract, related to the Charter of Christ.) [Cambridge University MS. Ff. 6. 34.]</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE>This treatise, entitled variously, <I>Carta Celestis Hereditatis, Chartre of Heuene, Charter of oure heuenli Eritage, Chartre of</I> 
<PB REF="00000223.tif" N="99"> <I>Heven Blisse, Diploma Caeli</I>, forms part of the <I>Poor Caitiff</I>, a work comprising a series of tracts, which has been ascribed to Richard Rolle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">See <I>Cat. of Camb. Univ. MSS.</I>, Vol. III (1858) under the description of MS. Ii. 6. 40, where this treatise is recorded with the title, <I>A Charter of remission</I>, and ascribed to Richard Rolle.</NOTE> to Wycliff,<NOTE PLACE="foot">By Mr. Wharton, according to <I>Cat. Harl. MSS. of Brit. Mus.</I> 1808, under MS. 1706. I do not know where Mr. Wharton makes this state|ment. This is ascribed to Wycliffe also by Robert Vaughan (<I>John de Wycliffe, D. D.</I>, 1853, Appendix, p. 533). See also <I>Cat. of Ash. MSS.</I> under MS. 1286, and <I>Report Hist. MSS. Com.</I> VIII (London, 1881) App. part III, 101, under Ashburnham MS. Add. 27<I>d</I>. Compare with these, Shirley, <I>Fasciculi Zizanorum</I>, Rolls Series (London, 1858), p. xiii, note 3 (referred to in this connection by ed. of <I>Cat. of Stowe MSS.</I>, 1895, Vol. I, 23).</NOTE> and to an unknown friar. So far as I know, the earliest MSS. date from the fourteenth century, and there are several of the fifteenth century.<NOTE PLACE="foot">The two oldest of which I have record are: MS. Ashburnham Add. 27<I>d</I> (See <I>Report Hist. MSS. Com.</I> VIII. App. part III, 101) of the fourteenth century. The others are MS. Bod. 4 (of which I do not know the date); MSS. Ashmole 1286 (about 1400); Douce 13, 288, 322; Rawl. C. 751; Bod. 938 (See Horstman, <I>Richard Rolle</I> I, 3), all of the fifteenth century; MSS. Harl. 1706, 2322, 2335, 2336, 4012, of which I do not know the dates; MS. Add. (Brit. Mus.) 30897, MS. Stowe 38, both of the fifteenth century; Camb. Univ. MSS. Ff. 5. 45, Ff. 6. 34, Ii. 6. 40, Hh. l. 12, all of the fifteenth century; Bibl. Nat. Paris, MS. angl. 41, <MILESTONE N="95a" UNIT="folio"> ff.</NOTE> On a "spare page" at the beginning of one of the manuscripts, Harl. 2336, is the following: <I>Dixit Episcopus Cicestrensis quod Frater Mi|nor compilavit hunc librum in suo Defensorio</I>. The compiler of the Harleian Catalogue from which I obtained this informa|tion, adds: "I doubt not but that this Bishop of Chichester was Reginald Pecok, who was thought to favor the Lollards, and was openly persecuted and deprived, as guilty of Heresy." It will be seen that the <I>Carta</I> of the <I>Poor Caitiff</I> is not a charter, in spite of its name, but a tract which discusses the Charter of Christ, its component parts, etc., and urges man to be mindful of it and to study it. Its relation to the <I>Charter of Christ</I> has been discussed in Chapter II.<NOTE PLACE="foot">John Bale has the following entry concerning another charter of the fourteenth century: "Brendanus monachus et abbas Hibernus, scrip|sit . . . . .<I>Cartam coelestis hereditatis</I>, li. 1. 'Quisquis sapiens heredi|tatem vendi.' [authority] <I>Ex domo Michaelis Hobley." Index Brit. Script.</I> ed. R. L. Poole, Oxf. 1902, pp. 49-50; and <I>Script. Illus. . . . . Catalogus</I> (post. pars), Basileae, 1559, p. 236. Concerning this work, Dr. Gustav Schirmer (<I>Zur Brendanus Legende</I>, Leipzig, 1888, pp. 10-11) expresses the opinion that the <I>Carta coelestis hereditatis</I> can not be attributed to St. Brendan. I have no means of arriving at a knowledge of the contents of this charter; but it would seem to me probable that it is a version of the <I>Carta Coelestis hereditatis</I>. The initial sentence of the <I>Carta</I> of Brendanus and that in the <I>Poor Caitiff</I> suggest a common origin, the <I>Poor Caitiff</I> Charter beginning, in one version. "Euery wise man &thorn;at cleyme&thorn; his eritage," and in another (MS. Douce 13) "Everie wise man that deynieth his heritage."</NOTE></HEADNOTE>
<P>
<PB REF="00000224.tif" N="100"><MILESTONE N="72" UNIT="folio">A good tretys of a notable chartour of pardoun of oure lorde Ihesu crist &amp;c. [in a different and later hand].</P>
<P>Euery wise man &thorn;at cleyme&thorn; his eritage. ei&thorn;ir aske&thorn; gret pardoun: kepi&thorn; bisili &amp; ha&thorn; ofte mynde vpon &thorn;e chartre of his calenge &verbar; &amp; &thorn;erfore eche man lerne to liue vertuously: &amp; kepe &amp; haue mynde vppon &thorn;e chartre of heuene blisse &verbar; &amp; stodie stidfastli &thorn;e witte of &thorn;is bille: for &thorn;e pardoun &thorn;erof schal dure wi&thorn;outen ende &verbar; vndirstonde wel &thorn;at &thorn;e chartre of his eritage, &amp; &thorn;e bulle of his euerlastinge pardoun: is oure lord ihesu crist. writen wi&thorn; al &thorn;e my&yogh;t &amp; vertu of god &verbar; &thorn;e parchemyn of &thorn;is heuenli chartre. is nei&thorn;ir of scheep ne of calf: but it is &thorn;e bodi &amp; &thorn;e blessid skyn of oure lord ihesu loomb &thorn;at neuere was spot|tid wi&thorn; wem of synne &verbar; &amp; was &thorn;ere neuere skyn of scheep nei&thorn;ir of calfe so sore &amp; so hard streined on &thorn;e teynture ei&thorn;ir harewe of eny parchemyn makere as was &thorn;e blessid bodi and skyn<MILESTONE N="72b" UNIT="folio"> of oure lord ihesu crist. for oure loue streined &amp; drawen vppon &thorn;e iebat of &thorn;e cros herde neuer man fro &thorn;e biginnyng of &thorn;e world til to now. ne&thorn;ir schal hens to domesdai: &thorn;at euere writere wroot vppon schepis skin ei&thorn;ir on calues wi&thorn; so hard &amp; hidouse pennes. so bittirli so sore &amp; so depe as writen &thorn;e cursid Iewis vppon &thorn;e blessid bodi &amp; swete skin of oure lord ihesu crist. wi&thorn; harde nailes. scharpe spere &amp; sore prickinge &thorn;ornes instide of here pennes &verbar; thei writen so sore &amp; so depe. &thorn;at &thorn;ei perciden hise hondes &amp; feet wi&thorn; harde nailes: &thorn;ei openeden his herte wi&thorn; a scharpe spere &verbar; &thorn;ei perssiden vppon his heed a corowne of 
<PB REF="00000225.tif" N="101"> scharpe &thorn;ornes &thorn;at licli perciden to his brayn panne &verbar; &thorn;e woundis vppon &thorn;at blessid bodi and swete skyn of crist: weren instide of lettris &verbar; &amp; as clerkis seyn &amp; specialli seint anselme. &thorn;ere weren vppon &thorn;e blessid bodi of crist open woundis bi noumbre fyue &thorn;ousend foure hundrid seuenti &amp; fyue &verbar; &thorn;is is &thorn;e noumbre of lettris: wi&thorn; whiche oure chartre was written &verbar; bi which we moun cleyme oure eritage. if we liven<MILESTONE N="73" UNIT="folio"> ri&yogh;tli: &amp; kepe &thorn;is chartre stidfastly in mynde &verbar; &thorn;e sentence &amp; vndir|stonding writen wi&thorn;inne &amp; wi&thorn;oute &thorn;is blessid chartre &amp; bodi of ihesu crist: is oure bileue &verbar; for he is &thorn;e cofre in whom is closid &amp; loken: al &thorn;e tresoure of witte &amp; wisdom of god &verbar; vppon &thorn;is blessid chartre. was writen weilinge. ei&thorn;ir mournynge. song &amp; sorwe &verbar; weilinge ei&thorn;ir mornynge; for sorwe of oure synnes &verbar; for &thorn;e whiche to ben helid &amp; waschen awey: crist god and man must suffre so hard &amp; peyneful woundis &verbar; vppon cristis bodi &thorn;at is oure heuenli charter: was writen singinge to alle &thorn;ilke &thorn;at parfiteli forsaken here synnes &verbar; for &thorn;ei han ful medicine &amp; helpe: &thorn;orou&yogh; vertu of the bittir woundis &amp; precios blood of ihesu &verbar; &amp; vppon &thorn;e woundis of ihesu mai be red sorwe. to alle hem &thorn;at for false likinge &amp; lust &thorn;at duri&thorn; but a while. bynden hem-self to synne &amp; seruage of &thorn;e fend &verbar; &amp; lesen &thorn;e help of &thorn;e heuenli chartre &amp; so here heritage; &amp; wenden blyndli to sorwe &thorn;at duri&thorn; for euere &verbar; &thorn;e laces of &thorn;is heuenli chartre: is &thorn;e biheeste of god &amp; &thorn;at god mai not lie. for he is souereyn treu&thorn;e &verbar; &thorn;e firste laas is his<MILESTONE N="73b" UNIT="folio"> biheeste; &thorn;at was dai ei&thorn;er oure a synful man ei&thorn;ir woman leue&thorn; here synne hooli &amp; hertli wi&thorn; bittir sorwe &amp; turne&thorn; hem to him; he schal receiue hem to his mercy &verbar; but eche man be war &thorn;at he tarie not longe; lest for his owne vnkyndenesse grace be taken fro him &verbar; &thorn;e secounde laas is &thorn;e ful trist &thorn;at we han &thorn;at god may not lie ne&thorn;ir be false of his biheefte &verbar; hereinne hangi&thorn; sikirli; oure trist of oure eritage &verbar; &amp; bi &thorn;ese two lacis hangi&thorn; &thorn;e seel of oure chartre; selid wi&thorn; &thorn;e blood of &thorn;e lomb crist &verbar; &thorn;at is cristis flessche taken of the clennest dropes of blood in &thorn;e swettest virgine <B>marie</B>; more craftili &amp; merueylousli. &thorn;an euere ony bee. bi craft of kynde gadri&thorn; &thorn;e wax of floures of &thorn;e feeld &verbar; &thorn;e printe<NOTE PLACE="foot">Transcript reads <I>prince</I>.</NOTE> of &thorn;is 
<PB REF="00000226.tif" N="102"> seel; is &thorn;e schap of oure lord ihesu crist hanginge for oure synne on &thorn;e cros. as we moun se bi &thorn;e ymage of &thorn;e crucifix &verbar; he ha&thorn; his heed bowid don; redi to kisse alle &thorn;ilke &thorn;at verili turnen to him he ha&thorn; hise armes spred abrood; redi to biclippe hem &verbar; he is nailed faste foot &amp; honde to &thorn;e crosse; for he wole duelle wi&thorn;<MILESTONE N="74" UNIT="folio"> hem &amp; neuere wende awey fro man; but if man forsake him first &thorn;orou&yogh; synne &verbar; he ha&thorn; al his bodi spred abrood: to &yogh;eue himself hoolly to vs cleuynge to him &verbar; vtterli he ha&thorn; his side opened; &amp; his herte cloue for or oure sake &verbar; so &thorn;at wi&thorn;oute lettinge we moun crepe in to cristis herte &amp; reste &thorn;ere &thorn;orou&yogh; stidfast bileue &amp; herti loue &verbar; &thorn;is chartre may not fiyr brenne ne watir drenche; nei&thorn;ir &thorn;eef robbe nei&thorn;ir ony crea|ture distroie &verbar; for &thorn;is scripture &thorn;e fadir of heuene haa&thorn; halewid ei&thorn;ir maad stidfast &verbar; &amp; sente it into &thorn;e world; &thorn;e whiche scrip|ture mai not be vndo as &thorn;e gospel witnessi&thorn; &verbar; &thorn;is scripture is oure lord Ihesu crist; chartre &amp; bulle of oure eritage of heuene &verbar; locke not &thorn;is chartre in &thorn;i coffre; but sette it ei&thorn;ir write it in &thorn;in herte &verbar; &amp; alle &thorn;e creatures in heuene nei&thorn;ir in er&thorn;e nei&thorn;ir in helle moun not robbe it nei&thorn;ir bireue it fro &thorn;e. but if &thorn;ou wolt &thorn;i self assentinge to synne &verbar; &amp; if &thorn;ou kepist weel &thorn;is chartre in &thorn;e coffre of &thorn;in herte wi&thorn; good liuynge &amp; deuote loue lastingli to &thorn;in ende &verbar; as tristeli &amp; treuli as he is trewe<MILESTONE N="74b" UNIT="folio"> god; &thorn;oroou&yogh; vertu of hise chartre &thorn;ou schalt haue &thorn;in eritage of blisse duringe wi&thorn;outen ende. . . . .</P>
